{"version":"1.2","person":{"datePublished":"2023-12-13","name":"Freskin de Moray","nameForms":[{"lang":"en","fullText":"Freskin de Moray","parts":[{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Given","value":"Freskin"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Surname","value":"de Moray"}],"order":"EUROTYPIC"}],"alternateName":"Freskin Moravia of Duffus and Strabrok","gender":"Male","lifespan":"1222–1269","fullLifespan":"1222–1269","birthDate":"+1222","birthPlace":{"address":"Duffus, Morayshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","geo":{"latitude":57.7,"longitude":-3.4,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"deathDate":"+1269","deathPlace":{"address":"Duffus, Morayshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","geo":{"latitude":57.7,"longitude":-3.4,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"userCertifiedLifeSummary":"Freskin de Moray (died c. 1269), Lord of Duffus and Strathbrock, was a Scottish noble.\n\nHe was the eldest son of Walter de Moravia and Euphemia de Ross. Freskin was a signatory of an agreement between Scotland and Wales in 1258, that the kingdoms would not make peace with King Henry III of England, without the consent of each other. Freskin died circa 1269 and was buried in the Chapel of St Lawrence, within the parish church of St Peter, Duffus. His lands where split in moieties between his daughters.\n\n«b»Marriage and issue«/b»\nFreskin married Joanna, Lady of Strathnaver, they are known to have had the following issue:\n\n1.) Mary de Moray, married Reginald le Chen, had issue.\n\n2.) Christian de Moray, married William de Fedderate, had issue.","events":[{"name":"Birth","sources":"0","year":"1222","date":"1222","place":"Duffus, Morayshire, Scotland, United Kingdom"},{"name":"Marriage","sources":"0","year":"1240","date":"about 1240","place":"Scotland","type":"Spousal","age":"18","id":"GXWH-CKR"},{"name":"Birth of Child","sources":"0","year":"1240","date":"about 1240","place":"Duffus, Elginshire, Scotland","age":"18","id":"GXWH-WB7"},{"name":"Death of Parent","sources":"0","year":"1263","date":"126